default3.1.1
default              
defaultThere are currently
default 84,197 people in prison, 80,323 men and 3,874 women. 10,786 of these prisoners are foreign nationals in detention. 
default&#xa0;
default3.1.2 
default              
defaultAccording to the government’s Updated Impact Assessment for the Offender Rehabilitation Bill,
default 
defaultif passed, around 13,000 offenders wi
defaultll be recalled or committed to custody, at a
defaultn additional
default cost of £16
default 
defaultmillion per year.
default  Further, prisons are required to cut up to 16% of their budgets next year.  This will mean losing more experienced staff.
default&#xa0;
default3.1.3 
default              
defaultIt is estimated that 36 per cent of p
defaultrisoners have a disability and approximately 25 per cent have a learning disability. In a recent Ministry of Justice study 49 per cent of female prisoners and 23 per cent of male prisoners were assessed as struggling with anxiety and depression. Levels of 
defaultself-harm are high amongst the prison population with 23,134 incidents taking place in the 12 months ending September 2012. Almost 50 per cent of women in prison have attempted suicide at some point in their lives. 
default&#xa0;
default3.1.4
default              
defaultThe prison population is ageing. 
defaultPrisoners over 60 are now the fastest growing group in prison. Many older people in prison have a physical health status 
defaultequivalent to a person
default 10 years
default their senior
default in the community, with a large number suffering from serious and terminal illnesses.
default&#xa0;
default3.1.
default5
default              
defaultA large proportion of those in prison have experienced social and economic disadvantage. Almost 50 per cent of the prison population 
defaultreport having no qualifications and approximately a quarter 
defaultof prisoners 
defaultneed help with basic literacy. 
defaultA
defaultround half of al
defaultl prisoners have histories of debt and 15 per cent report being homeless prior to custody.
default&#xa0;
default3.1.6
default              
defaultThere are around 12,000 men, and a small number of women, serving 
defaultindeterminate sentences
default. The average sentence length has increased so that 
default prisoners
default 
defaulton a l
defaultife sentence 
defaulttypically spend 15 to 20 years behind bars.  The number of lifers has doubled since the introduction of the now defunct indeterminate sentence for public protection in 2003. Each 
defaultindeterminate sentenced 
defaultprisoner costs the taxpayer around 
default£600,000 – £800,000 for their term inside.
default&#xa0;default3.1
default.7
default              
defaultThe indeterminate sentence is focused on public safety, reducing the risk the prisoner poses and making sure that the person is safely released at the right time to a sustainable community plan on 
defaultlicence
default. 
defaultAccording to a recent report
default by HMI Probation and HMI Prisons, 
default95% to 98% are resettled safely. The inspection report indicated that “assumptions were often made that life sentence prisoners knew all about ‘the system’ which led to an underestimation of t
defaulthe amount 
defaultof advice and help they needed”.  It also found that “
defaultsentence planning was weak and probation staff struggled to design meaningful objectives for those who appeared to have done all required work in custody.”
default&#xa0;
default3.1
default.9
default              
defaultAs the proposed cuts to legal
default aid are brought in
default and wider cuts to criminal justice bite
default, systems will inevitably become more stretched and mistakes will be made. 
defaultPrisons on limited budgets are providing less training for existing staff and newly recruited staff are not required to ha
defaultve any formal educational qualifications.  This means that prison staff are less able to provide information or advice about the complex legislative framework that governs individual sentences. 
defaultIt is therefor
defaulte even more important that
default prisoners can get ind
defaultependent and expert advice to 
defaultprogress through their sentence appropriately towards safe release. Criminal legal aid for prison law currently plays a vital role in getting 
defaultthe journey to release
default right.  It is often vital to ensure that prisoners ge
defaultt on the
default right courses
default, progress when appropriate to an open prison so they can properly prepare for safe community living and secure appropriate release packages.  All of this work is currently done by lawyers for fixed fees 
defaultf
defaultor around £220.
default&#xa0;
default3.1.10
default              
defaultThe inevitabl
defaulte consequence 
defaultof ending access to independent and skilled legal representatives 
defaultwill be that prisoners will spend longer in closed conditio
defaultns and longer in open prisons
default at immense public expense
default. 
defaultIf, as a result of the lack of legal advice and challenge, t
defaulthe 12,000 prisoners on life sentences and IPPs spend an extra year in jail – and only one year is a conservative estimate – this will cost £480 million. This sum dwarfs the £4 million the Ministry of Justice
default hopes to save by
default the ending of legal aid to pris
defaultoners.
default  Public confidence could 
defaulthardly be more affected than by ending a relatively cheap and effective means to secure rehabilitation for prisoners where is not happening as a matter of course.  One shocking consequence of the changes is that prisoners wh
defaulto have made sufficient progress to be awarded a review of their suitability to move to open conditions prior to actual release
default will be deprived of legal aid for representation.  Most will be forced to represent themselves at their parole hearing and will 
defaulthave no choice but to 
defaultquestion 
defaultpersonally 
defaultprofessional witnesses as to their assessment of their risk to obtain a fair hearing. 
defaultPrisoners would therefore need to be provided with all the documentation that has hitherto been given to their lawyers, includin
defaultg details about victims.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default4.1
default              
defaultThe Justice Secretary has said that prisoners, including children, don’t need lawyers because they can complain. 
defaultMany of the serious issues that Howard League lawyers deal with every day, such as making sure children have a safe place to go to when they leave jail are not suitable for backwards looking complaints systems. A complaints system can only rectify mistakes
default once they have been made, often incurring many months delay. Lawyers representing prisoners with 
defaultsentence planning
default and resettlement help to prevent mistakes.
default&#xa0;
default4.2
default              
defaultEven with help from lawyers, the complaints system has been inadequate to protect 
defaultprisoners 
defaultfrom abuse behind closed doors
default.
default The Howard League has represented children and young adults who have been subjected to unlawful punishments, physical restraints resulting in broken limbs, and moves to mental health facilities. Without legal action these wo
defaultuld not have been remedied and the abuse would have continued.
default.
default&#xa0;
default4.
default3
default              
defaultSince July 2010, the legal aid rules have restricted lawyers from claiming for legal aid for issues that could be resolved through the complaints system.  As a consequence, 
defaultthe 
defaultHoward Le
defaultague
default 
defaultlegal team has considerable experience of conducting complaints on behalf of young people who cannot navigate the system themselves
default.
default 
defaultBecause this work is not covered by legal aid, the charity has had to provide it on a pro bono basis, supported from limited charitable funding. 
defaultOur experience of this work highlights the numerous problems with the complaints system as a form of redress wh
defaulten compared to the benefits of legal representation:
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default5.1
default              
defaultThe availability of judicial review for prisoners in the future is unclear pending the further consultation on judicial review and the i
defaultmpact of the residence test on this group: it cannot be said to act as a safety net.  Our lawyers resolve cases simply and efficiently every day.  Although many of these cases could technically turn into judicial review cases, it is in everyone’s interests
default to fix the problem as quickly as possible.
default  
default5.2
default              
defaultOn the rare occasion that
default judicial review
defaults
default become necessary,
default it is vitally important that prisoners are not barred from bringing them due to technical hurdles
default. 
defaultThe response by APL sets out the technical 
defaultdifficulties that will be posed by the new residence test and the way in which judicial review work is structured. We are deeply concerned that the Justice Secretary relies on the availability of legal aid for judicial review as an excuse for withdrawing c
defaultriminal legal aid for prisoners’ legal problems while at the same time proposing to drastically curtail the availability of legal aid for judicial review.
default5.3
default              
defaultThe proposed changes to judicial review include not only restrictions on legal aid which will mea
defaultn that lawyers may simply not be able to burden the financial risk of bringing claims on behalf of individuals but also restricting the right of interest groups to bring claims in the public interest.  Although we appreciate that the new proposals to restr
defaultict standing are not within the Committee’s ambit, we are concerned that the combination means that organisations like us will no longer be able to assist individuals or raise points of principle.  Our case work over the years has done both, with great ben
defaultefits to children in prison.  For instance, a case brought on behalf of 14 year old K
default paved the way for all children to have a right to an oral hearing before the parole board whereas the Children Act case
default brought in the Howard League’s own name secured 
defaultchild protection rights for all children in the secure estate.
default6.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultChanges to legal aid for prison law and judicial review defaultwill be defaultdisastrous for the safety and rights of children and young people in prison.default default6.1
default              
defaultThe Howard League legal team has represented hu
defaultndreds of children in prisons and privately run secure training centres to help them to progress 
defaultmore safely
default through their incarceration and to make sure the arrangements for their resettlement are safe and supportive. Legal aid to pay for this work 
defaultwill b
defaulte
default essentially abolished.
default  The only criminal legal aid for prison law will relate to parole hearings where release is possible or disciplinary hearings where a magistrate may impose 
defaultadditional days.  
defaultYet, t
defaulthese cases affect a small proportion of children.  
defaultThis is because all other aspects of the criminal justice system are based on the principle that children should be treated differently fro
defaultm adults. 
defaultHence, most children are detained under Detention and Training Orders.  Although there is no power to 
defaultimpose additional days on children serving such sentences, poor behaviour that might have led to a disciplinary hearing by a judge in the case of an adult, can equally lead to penalties such as the imposition of an electronic tag on release or not getting 
defaultearly release at all.  Yet children will have no access to a lawyer to deal with these issues unless the high threshold for judicial review is met.
default6.2
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultNot only will this mean that children will not get
default onto
default the courses they need to address their offending or 
defaultthe local authority support to reintegrate safely into the community, but it also means that our lawyers won’t find out about any serious abuse going on inside the prison. Access to an expert lawyer, who is on their side, who helps the children to get thei
defaultr entitlements and help to settle back home is one of the key ways we can all find out about what is going on inside jails.
default6.3
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe relationship of trust built up between Howard League lawyers and children in custody has shown them that the law can be a force 
defaultfor good, one of the essential components of respect for the law and responsible citizenship.
