default6.5
default              
defaultThe availability of advocates in prisons is not sufficient reaso
defaultn to dispense with legal advice and representation.  The advocates provide a vital service, but it is different from a legal service.  The advocates were required because of the immense level of need faced by children in prison. The contracts for such serv
defaultices (which are not new) require that the advocates resolve things at the lowest level: they are not to 
defaultprovide legal advice
default, nor indeed would they be capabl
defaulte
default of so doing as they have no legal training or expertise.
default6.6
default              
defaultThe nuts and bolts of the work the H
defaultoward League’s team undertakes under fixed fees for children concerns serious and important issues – all of which will no longer be available.  This includes:
default&#xa0;
defaultResettlementdefault 
defaultwork for children in prison: defaultThis is work preparing the ground for release on 
defaultlicence
default or under supervision, ensuring that an appropriate accommodation and 
defaulta 
defaultsupport package is in place for release. This is vital for a smooth transition back into the local community. Release may be del
defaultayed because this work will no longer be continued and this will increase the overall costs of detaining a child.  Around 70 per cent of children reoffend.  It is well known that inadequate accommodation and support are linked to reoffending.  Getting the 
defaultright package of support for children on release from custody is critical to the success of the Ministry of Justice’s rehabilitation revolution. 
default&#xa0;
defaultPre-tariff reviewsdefault: These are very rare for children and young people.  The system is that those who make goo
defaultd progress are entitled to be considered for an early review to see if they can progress to open conditions where they will be able to prepare for release and return to education and work.  Most young people will require legal help in securing such a revie
defaultw. That will no longer be available.  Those who are granted such a review without legal assistance will not have any legal representation at their hearing.   These 
defaultchildren
default 
defaultand young people 
defaultwill be expected to represent themselves, question witnesses and 
defaultp
defaultrepare the case.  It is absurd to think that a young person could have a fair hearing in such circumstances.  Yet there is 
defaultno provision
default for any flexibility to fund such cases.
